  "prompt": "What is the Romeo and Juliet law?",
  "response": "The \"Romeo and Juliet law\" is a term commonly used to refer to legal provisions that allow for some leniency in statutory rape cases involving individuals who are close in age. These laws are designed to prevent the prosecution of young people who engage in consensual sexual activities when they are close in age and one or both are below the age of consent.\n\nThe specifics of Romeo and Juliet laws can vary significantly by jurisdiction. Generally, they provide exceptions or reduced penalties for sexual activities between minors or between a minor and someone just above the age of consent. For example, a state might have an age of consent set at 18 but allow for consensual sexual activity between a 16-year-old and an 18-year-old without prosecuting the older partner for statutory rape.\n\nThe purpose of these laws is to recognize that consensual relationships between peers do not carry the same potential for exploitation and harm as relationships between minors and significantly older adults.\n\nIt's important to consult the specific statutes in your jurisdiction to understand the precise conditions and limitations of these laws, as they vary widely across different regions.",
